t has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert de Chanteloup was born in 1215, in Chanteloup, Manche, Normandy, France as the son of Foulques de Chanteloup. He had at least 1 son."},"et":{"1215–":"1215–Surnud","1215–Male":"1215–Surnud","1245–Male":"1245–Surnud","1190–1228":"1190–1228","1228":"1228","1190":"1190","1215":"1215","1245":"1245","Chanteloup, Manche, Normandy, France":"Chanteloup, Manche, Normandie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1215–":"1215–Kuollut","1215–Male":"1215–Kuollut","1245–Male":"1245–Kuollut","1190–1228":"1190–1228","1228":"1228","1190":"1190","1215":"1215","1245":"1245","Chanteloup, Manche, Normandy, France":"Chanteloup, Manche, Normandie, Ranska"},"fr":{"1215–":"1215–Décédé","1215–Male":"1215–Décédé","1245–Male":"1245–Décédé","1190–1228":"1190–1228","1228":"1228","1190":"1190","1215":"1215","1245":"1245","Chanteloup, Manche, Normandy, France":"Chanteloup, Manche, Normandie, France","lifeSummary":"Robert de Chanteloup est né en 1215, à Chanteloup, Manche, Normandie, France, fils de Foulques de Chanteloup. Il a eu au moins 1 fils."},"de":{"1215–":"1215–Verstorben","1215–Male":"1215–Verstorben","1245–Male":"1245–Verstorben","1190–1228":"1190–1228","1228":"1228","1190":"1190","1215":"1215","1245":"1245","Chanteloup, Manche, Norma